    "content": "Searching 'best Ayurveda doctor near me' returns a lot of results, but very few search results actually tell you whether a practitioner is qualified, appropriately specialized for your condition, or safe. Here is a concrete 5-step process to evaluate any Ayurveda doctor before booking a consultation.\n\n## Step 1: Verify BAMS and Council Registration\n\nThe baseline qualification for any legitimate Ayurveda doctor is a **BAMS** (Bachelor of Ayurvedic Medicine and Surgery) degree from a recognized institution, plus active registration with the relevant state Ayurveda medical council and, in India, the national Ayurveda medical council framework (historically CCIM). Ask directly for the registration number — a legitimate practitioner will provide this without hesitation. If a practitioner cannot or will not provide registration details, treat that as a serious red flag rather than an oversight.\n\n## Step 2: Check Specialization Match\n\nAyurveda has distinct specializations, and matching your condition to the right one matters:\n\n- **Panchakarma** for detoxification and rejuvenation programs\n- **Kayachikitsa** for general chronic internal conditions\n- **Prasuti Tantra** for women's reproductive health\n- **Shalya/Shalakya** for surgical and ENT/eye conditions\n- **Manasika** for mental health concerns\n\nA BAMS generalist can handle many common concerns, but for a specific chronic condition, look for a doctor with an MD in the relevant branch rather than defaulting to whoever is closest or most heavily advertised.\n\n## Step 3: Ask About Experience With Your Specific Condition\n\nGeneral years of practice matters less than specific experience with your condition. It's reasonable to directly ask a prospective doctor: how many patients with this condition have you treated, and what does a typical treatment plan and timeline look like? A doctor confident in their approach should be able to answer this clearly rather than giving vague reassurance.\n\n## Step 4: Check Patient Reviews (With Judgment)\n\nReviews can be useful for gauging communication style, clinic environment, and follow-through, but treat any review claiming a 'complete cure' for a serious chronic condition with skepticism — recovery experiences vary significantly by individual, and a small number of glowing anecdotes is not clinical evidence.\n\n## Step 5: Understand Consultation Fee and Protocol Upfront\n\nBefore committing to a treatment plan, especially multi-week Panchakarma programs, get a clear written breakdown of the consultation fee, the number of sessions or days required, and the total expected cost. Reputable practitioners are transparent about this upfront rather than revealing costs incrementally as treatment progresses.\n\n## Warning Signs to Avoid\n\nBe cautious of practitioners or clinics that show any of these patterns:\n\n- **Guaranteed cures** — no legitimate medical practitioner, in any system of medicine, can honestly guarantee a cure for a serious chronic condition.\n- **'Secret family formulas'** — while some formulations do have proprietary variations, a refusal to explain basic ingredients or mechanism, combined with premium pricing, is a common pattern in less credible practices.\n- **No diagnostic Pariksha** — a proper Ayurveda consultation includes some form of structured assessment (history-taking, pulse diagnosis, physical examination). A practitioner who prescribes a treatment plan without any real assessment is skipping a foundational step.\n\n## Where to Start\n\nYou can browse verified practitioner profiles, filtered by specialization and location, at [/doctors](/doctors). If you're specifically looking in Kerala, see our dedicated guide to [best Ayurveda doctors in Kerala](/best-ayurveda-doctors-kerala); if you're based in the UAE, see our guide to [Ayurveda hospitals in Dubai](/ayurveda-hospitals-dubai)."
